The posterior predictive uncertainty is represented by ribbons displaying the posterior 90% uncertainty interval on the mean trend. In lecture we referred to this as the confidence interval on the mean.

posterior_linpred(mod3_Bayesian, newdata = viz_grid) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% tibble::as_tibble() %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column("post_id") %>% 
  pivot_longer(!c("post_id"), names_to = 'pred_id') %>% 
  mutate(across(.cols = 'pred_id', .fns = as.numeric)) %>% 
  group_by(pred_id) %>% 
  summarise(num_post = n(),
            trend_avg = mean(value),
            trend_lwr = quantile(value, 0.05),
            trend_upr = quantile(value, 0.95)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  left_join(viz_grid %>% tibble::rowid_to_column("pred_id"),
            by = "pred_id") %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = xn_07)) +
  geom_ribbon(mapping = aes(ymin = trend_lwr,
                            ymax = trend_upr,
                            fill = as.factor(xb_07)),
              alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(y = trend_avg,
                          color = as.factor(xb_07)),
                size = 1.) +
  facet_wrap(~xb_07, labeller = "label_both") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d("xb_07") +
  scale_color_viridis_d("xb_07") +
  labs(y = "mean trend") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

According to the above figures, it was obviously seen that the mean trend linearly decreased with the input xn_07. Also we can see that the mean trend decreased when we increased the variable xb_07. The xn_07 and xb_07 variables are the additive effect on the mean trend.
